        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat: channel echo / session pinning",
        "body": "## Channel echo / session pinning — with native streaming echo\n\nMirror a session's turns to additional pinned channels (\"echo targets\"), so a\nconversation that lives in one place can be followed (and continued) from another.\nWorks across surfaces — a turn from Telegram, the web app, the control UI, or the CLI\nmirrors to the pinned target(s), because every surface shares the same session key.\n\n### What gets echoed, and how\n\n- **Prompt** → mirrored with a `📱 [via <channel>]` marker (it genuinely originated\n  elsewhere, so the marker is honest).\n- **Response** → delivered **natively** on each pinned channel:\n  - **Native-final (A):** the response mirrors un-prefixed, so it reads as a real reply\n    (not a tagged `[echo]` copy). `fireEchoDeliveries` gained a `{ prefixed: false }` opt-out;\n    both echo paths (the `message:sent` hook and the `chat.send` web/CLI path) use it.\n  - **Native streaming (B-full):** when a pinned channel has a streaming renderer and\n    streaming is enabled, the response renders **live** on that channel — the single\n    agent run is replayed into the channel's own draft, editing one message as tokens\n    arrive (no second agent run). Telegram ships the first renderer.\n\n**Coexistence, not replacement.** The post-hoc final-text mirror is retained as the\n**fallback**: it serves stream-off targets and channels without a renderer yet (only\nTelegram has one), and reconciles a dropped partial. A target handled by a live renderer\nis gated out of the post-hoc mirror (per-run handled marks) so it never double-delivers.\n\n### Mechanism (no compositor extraction, no N agent runs)\n\nThe origin runs the agent **once**; its streaming events already broadcast on the\nagent-event bus by `runId`. A per-target **mirror resolver** (`echo-mirror-resolver.ts`)\nreplays that bus into the target channel's own `on*` callbacks; the **fan-out**\n(`echo-streaming.ts`) launches one resolver + one channel renderer per streaming target\nat run start, and gates the post-hoc mirror for handled targets. Telegram's renderer\n(`extensions/telegram/echo-renderer.ts`) drives the same `createTelegramDraftStream`\nprimitive the native compositor uses. Channels register via the\n`openclaw/plugin-sdk/channel-echo` surface (first-wins, documented ownership contract).\n\n### Tests\n\n~1,200 lines across 7 suites: echo target resolution + delivery (`echo.test.ts`),\nmirror resolver replay/ordering/isolation, fan-out + registry + per-run gating,\nTelegram renderer, and the gateway session-echo methods. `tsgo` clean.\n\n### Live streaming proof — webchat → Telegram\n\nB-full's live streaming is a **stack-dependency**: the live progress-draft streaming +\nthe CLI streaming parser come from the persist/commentary PRs, so the *isolated* branch\ncan't show it. Captured on a **combined build** (this PR + the persist/commentary stack\n+ #89851 MCP-loopback transport, 3-way-ported zero-conflict), in a crabbox on a **test\nbot** (never the daily driver). A webchat `chat.send` turn pinned to echo into a Telegram\nsupergroup, response from a deterministic word-by-word model:\n\n```\n[fanout] target=telegram:<supergroup> factory=yes renderer=yes\n[render] onPartialReply len=3\n[render] onPartialReply len=9          # response text grows word-by-word\n… 35 streamed deltas → 35 onPartialReply\n[finalize] msgId=40 liveEdits=4        # ONE telegram message, EDITED 4x live\ntelegram outbound send ok messageId=39 # ONLY the prompt echo — no post-hoc duplicate\n```\n\nPer turn the pinned chat shows `📱 [via webchat] <prompt>` + the **response message\ngrowing word-by-word** (one message, live-edited), with no duplicate final.\n\n### Open maintainer decisions (flagged by review)\n\n- **Privacy/authorization/operator-warning/docs** for persistent `echoTargets` mirroring\n  future session content across transports — a maintainer policy decision before this is a\n  supported surface.\n- **Public `plugin-sdk/channel-echo` surface** — ownership contract is now documented +\n  first-wins; sign-off on it as a stable public subpath is a maintainer call.\n- Live streaming proof is necessarily on the combined stack (see above); the PR's own code\n  (renderer + fan-out + gating, incl. the chat.send + double-delivery fixes) is fully tested.\n",
        "branch": "rfc/channel-echo",
